    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Challenging affirmative action on meritocratic grounds argues that race-based policies inherently violate the principle that success should be determined solely by individual achievement and effort. By allocating resources based on group identity rather than personal capability, these programs may inadvertently undermine the skills and achievements of recently admitted students who lack the institutional advantages of their peer group. Furthermore, such policies can solidify racial categorization in higher education, potentially delaying a societal shift toward individualism and colorblind evaluation. Ultimately, true equity is better achieved through institutional accountability and unrestricted access that focus on individual outcomes rather than group-based-handed.",
